2026-07-16 FIX, and this one was LIVE on a recruiter-facing artifact: the map shipped durable-state v1.0.0, which carries TWO known-root-caused defects. (1) EXPORT LIED: v1's download() calls a.click() (dropped, the artifact iframe sandbox has no allow-downloads) and navigator.clipboard.writeText() (rejects, clipboard-write is never delegated to a cross-origin frame, and the async rejection escapes a sync try/catch), then the toolbar printed "Exported (downloaded and copied to clipboard)" UNCONDITIONALLY. Both halves false. (2) RESET WAS DEAD: the guard read `if(!confirm(...)) return;` and confirm() returns undefined in the sandbox (no allow-modals), so !undefined bailed on every click.
  FIX: swapped in the v2.0.0 block lifted verbatim from living-resume.html, the only copy production-verified against a real clipboard sentinel. download() is REMOVED (the name was the lie); exportState() returns {json,copied} driven off execCommand('copy')'s real boolean, and there is deliberately NO `downloaded` field because that fact is unknowable in-sandbox and an absent field cannot be misreported. confirmReset defaults off, so Reset works.
  VERIFIED IN A REAL BROWSER: version 2.0.0 live, download() absent, exportState present, zero JS errors, all 8 tabs render, data intact (41 companies / 48 relationships / 8 chokepoints). THE CONTROL IS THE POINT: called exportState() with NO user gesture, and it reported copied:false. execCommand cannot succeed without transient activation, so a truthful implementation MUST say false there. v1 would have claimed success. LIMIT OF THIS EVIDENCE, stated plainly: this was tested at a localhost top-level origin, NOT inside the cross-origin sandboxed iframe where the bug actually bites, so it proves the message is DERIVED rather than hardcoded; the definitive sandbox proof is the earlier cross-origin sentinel run against this same v2 block.
  ALSO: the file now contains ZERO raw non-ASCII bytes. The v2 block shipped literal glyphs and they rendered as mojibake ("a-w Export") when served without a charset, same class as the raw middot in the title earlier today. Toolbar glyphs are now JS \u escapes (textContent means HTML entities would render literally), and the user-facing importJSON error string's curly apostrophe is escaped too. RULE: never ship a raw non-ASCII byte in a file whose charset the host controls.
  STILL OPEN: business-framework-toolkit.html is ALSO on v1.0.0 and its Export lies the same way. Out of scope for this repo, but it is his artifact and a user clicking Export there is told a falsehood.
